zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#67339.body:
On Zephyr v3.3, I2C transfers work correctly on the SAM E70.
On Zephyr v3.5, the same I2C transfers are failing.

```
const struct device *const i2c_dev = DEVICE_DT_GET(DT_NODELABEL(twihs0));
int main(void)
{
    while(1) {
        uint8_t wbuf[1] = {IIC_TEMP_INTERNAL_ADDR};
        uint8_t rbuf[2] = {0,0};
        i2c_write_read(i2c_dev, LOC_IIC_TEMP1_ADDR, wbuf, sizeof(wbuf), rbuf, sizeof(rbuf));
        uint16_t result = (((uint16_t) rbuf[0] << 8) | ((uint16_t) rbuf[1] ));
        k_sleep(K_MSEC(100));
    }
    return 0;
}
```
This is a logic analyzer trace of the transfer under v3.3
![i2c-good-trace-tight](https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/assets/12721085/e82d0c2a-f202-4ea8-9861-bb1e96af6b47)
This is a trace of the transfer under v3.5.  The controller stops after the intial write.
![i2c-failed-trace-tight](https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/assets/12721085/9383d750-ac2e-4ae5-a635-9ba45b48c4ed)

There were some changes to i2c_sam_twihs.c, same70.dtsi and atmel,sam-i2c-twihs.yaml relating to the clock control but selectively reverting those changes doesn't seem to fix the issue on v3.5.

In my full application, other clocks for UDP, UARTS, etc work fine.

Is there a config or devicetree setting that I missed adding during the upgrade?

zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#70097.body:
## Introduction

It is possible to control the sampling of an ADC in a ST controller with a timer. Also there is an option to pass trigger signals to the timers. My idea would be to extend the existing API with this feature, add flags to the configurations where necessary. Maybe make it configurable with a Kconfig option to enable the feature.
We designed an ASIC with counters and timers of similar functionality and I'm sure other controllers have these as well.

### Problem description

I would like to trigger an ADC from a counter / timer (e.g. TIM1), over a defined time t<sub>meas</sub>. This time is measured with e. g. TIM2, and will stop TIM1 once TIM2 reaches the top value. For this, I need to be able to setup the output trigger of TIM1 and tell the ADC to listen to this trigger. This might also be a feature that could be added to for the ADC API. Then, once TIM2 reaches top, it will stop TIM1 from counting.

### Proposed change

`CONFIG_COUNTER_HW_TRG_SUPPORT=y` enables this feature (name is up for debate). There are flags provided in the API to tell the configurations that they are the source of an output trigger, or to set / clear the channel of the counter. Furthermore, there is a new configuration structure counter_in_trg_cfg and function where a hardware input trigger line can be setup. The number of input trigger lines, output triggers and output channels must be specified in counter_config_info.

## Detailed RFC

The idea is to support hardware input trigger lines as well as output channels and output triggers for the counter / timer modules.

### Proposed change (Detailed)

Changes in Kconfig:
I think this feature should be configurable, as not every timer might support this and it is not always desired. This might save code size. Thus, I propose to add a kconfig option to enable this feature.

Changes in the API:
The most happens in the API itself. First, I propose to add three new members in the counter_config_info structure, something along
```c
struct counter_config_info {
	/* existing members */

#if IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_COUNTER_HW_TRG_SUPPORT)
	/**
	 * Number of input triggers available.
	 */
	uint8_t n_in_trgs;
	/**
	 * Number of output channels available.
	 */
	uint8_t n_out_ch;
	/**
	 * Number of output triggers available.
	 */
	uint8_t n_out_trg;
#endif /* IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_COUNTER_HW_TRG_SUPPORT) */
};
```

Next, I'd add a structure and function to define an input trigger line. The function and structure are similar to those of the alarm. The description for the callback in the alarm should be adjusted to that the callback must be provided if no output is specified and is optional otherwise. The newly added structure and function might look as follows.
```c
typedef void (*counter_in_trg_callback_t)(const struct device *dev, uint8_t id, void *user_data);
struct counter_in_trg_cfg {
	/**
	 * Index of the source for the input trigger line.
	 */
	uint32_t source;
	/**
	 * Callback function. If set, the interrupt (if available) is enabled for the input trigger.
	 */
	counter_in_trg_callback_t callback;
	/**
	 * User data passed to callback function (not valid if callback is NULL).
	 */
	void *user_data;
	/**
	 * Flags (see @ref COUNTER_IN_TRIGGER_FLAGS).
	 */
	uint32_t flags;
};

/**
 * Description.
 */
__syscall int counter_set_input_trigger(const struct device *dev, uint8_t id, const struct counter_in_trg_cfg *trg_cfg);

static inline int z_impl_counter_set_input_trigger(const struct device *dev, uint8_t id, const struct counter_in_trg_cfg *trg_cfg)
{
	const struct counter_driver_api *api =
				(struct counter_driver_api *)dev->api;

	if (id >= counter_get_num_of_in_trg(dev)) {
		return -ENOTSUP;
	}

	return api->set_in_trg(dev, id, trg_cfg);
}
```
The api must be extended by additional functions. These are `counter_set_input_trigger()`, `counter_get_num_of_in_trg()`, `counter_get_num_of_out_trg()`, and `counter_get_num_of_out_ch()`. Also the counter_driver_api structure must be extended by one new function pointer.

The flags of the input trigger should support edge detection. The idea is to leave it open to the user what happens, if neither are used (bypass or error) and if both are used (both edges or error).
```c
/**
 * @anchor COUNTER_IN_TRIGGER_FLAGS
 * @name Flags used by counter_in_trg_cfg.
 * @{
 */
#define COUNTER_IN_TRG_CFG_POS_EDGE BIT(0)
#define COUNTER_IN_TRG_CFG_NEG_EDGE BIT(1)
/**@} */
```

It should be possible to specify an output for the input trigger, top, and maybe even alarm. The idea is that maybe a macro exists to specify channel set, channel clear, and output trigger source. I'm uncertain whether it should be part of the already existing flag, or if another option should be added to the structures with a meaningful name and instructions.
```c
/**
 * If set, the specified configuration is the source of the output trigger `n`.
 */
#define COUNTER_OUTPUT_TRG_SOURCE(n) BIT(8 + 3 * n + 0)
/**
 * If set, the specified configuration clears the output channel `n`.
 */
#define COUNTER_OUTPUT_CH_CLEAR(n) BIT(8 + 3 * n + 1)
/**
 * If set, the specified configuration sets the output channel `n`.
 */
#define COUNTER_OUTPUT_CH_SET(n) BIT(8 + 3 * n + 2)
```

Another approach would be to add functions for the different output types and an enumerate for the different sources of the outputs. Something like (naming is up for debate)
```c
enum counter_output_source {
	COUNTER_OUTPUT_SOURCE_TOP,
	COUNTER_OUTPUT_SOURCE_ALARM,
	COUNTER_OUTPUT_SOURCE_INPUT_TRIGGER,
};

enum counter_output_channel {
	COUNTER_OUTPUT_CHANNEL_BYPASS,
	COUNTER_OUTPUT_CHANNEL_CLEAR,
	COUNTER_OUTPUT_CHANNEL_SET,
};

__syscall int counter_set_out_trg(const struct device *dev, uint8_t id, enum counter_output_source src);
/* implementation here */

__syscall int counter_set_out_ch(const struct device *dev, uint8_t id, enum counter_output_source src, enum counter_output_channel mode);
/* implementation here */
```
Maybe it is possible to instruct the users to define their own flags for the corresponding configurations.

In the end, there shouldn't be too many changes, only an additional feature.

### Dependencies

If this feature is deactivated by default, it shouldn't impact any of the existing projects.
Should the config option be left out, there's still not too much impact, however, the implementations should be extended by the new feature (even a simple `return -ENOSYS` should do the trick). This is to prevent NULL-pointer dereferencing when calling an API function.
On the zephyr side, the implementation of the different counters should be extended to support the new feature, which may come with some work and research. The research comes from flipping through the instruction manuals of the different manufacturers to see whether their controller supports these hardware trigger lines.
Maybe a devicetree property might be of help there.

### Concerns and Unresolved Questions

I'm uncertain about the approach of the output trigger / channel. I feel like I'm overlooking the obvious there.
In general, is this a feasible approach? Does it benefit the zephyr rtos? Are there optimizations, or better generalizations?
List any concerns, unknowns, and generally unresolved questions etc.

## Alternatives

There aren't that many alternatives. I tried to stick with the way the counter API is set up. As already mentioned, this might also be an useful feature for the ADC. 
An alternative would be to leave the API as is, then extend it in the framework of my company. The issue with this is that the maintaining could become a bit tricky, depending on the changes that might or might not come in the future. The advantage is that some less general use-cases could be depicted, depending on the hardware.

zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#86406.body:
**Is your enhancement proposal related to a problem? Please describe.**
STM32 eth driver starts to be cluttered with `#if DT_HAS_COMPAT_STATUS_OKAY(st_stm32h7_ethernet)` directives when it comes to accessing directly some registers.
For instance: 
```
#if DT_HAS_COMPAT_STATUS_OKAY(st_stm32h7_ethernet)
		if (config->promisc_mode) {
			heth->Instance->MACPFR |= ETH_MACPFR_PR;
		} else {
			heth->Instance->MACPFR &= ~ETH_MACPFR_PR;
		}
#else
		if (config->promisc_mode) {
			heth->Instance->MACFFR |= ETH_MACFFR_PM;
		} else {
			heth->Instance->MACFFR &= ~ETH_MACFFR_PM;
		}
#endif /* DT_HAS_COMPAT_STATUS_OKAY(st_stm32h7_ethernet) */
```
This is because IP matching this compatible has a set of register which naming differs from the other STM32 IPs, but are otherwise functionally compatible.

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Provide abstraction functions to access these registers to relieve the code from these cluttered pieces.
For instance:
```
__STATIC_INLINE void stm32_eth_set_promisc_mode(ETH_HandleTypeDef *heth, bool promisc_mode_on)
{
#if DT_HAS_COMPAT_STATUS_OKAY(st_stm32h7_ethernet)
		if (promisc_mode_on) {
			heth->Instance->MACPFR |= ETH_MACPFR_PR;
		} else {
			heth->Instance->MACPFR &= ~ETH_MACPFR_PR;
		}
#else
		if (promisc_mode_on) {
			heth->Instance->MACFFR |= ETH_MACFFR_PM;
		} else {
			heth->Instance->MACFFR &= ~ETH_MACFFR_PM;
		}
#endif /* DT_HAS_COMPAT_STATUS_OKAY(st_stm32h7_ethernet) */
}
```

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Split the driver in 2 between H7 compatible and non H7 compatible. Though, this will likely double the maintenance burden and doesn't prevent the case of occur again with a next series providing new set of register names, while the abstraction functions could easily deal with that.

**Additional context**
See https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/pull/86315/files as a PR adding more matter to this topic.

zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#90252.body:
**Describe the bug**

On STM32H747xI, partitions defined close to the end of the first Flash bank are causing runtime errors like the following:
```
*** Booting Zephyr OS build v3.7.0-16360-gd851814b6c4d ***
[00:00:00.207,000] <err> flash_stm32h7: Range ovelaps flash bank discontinuity
```
as reported in https://github.com/arduino/ArduinoCore-zephyr/pull/125#issuecomment-2894555895 .


**To Reproduce**

The partition that is causing the error is defined by this DTS snippet:

```C
&flash0 {
        partitions {
                user_sketch: partition@e0000 {
                        reg = <0x0e0000 0x20000>;
                };
        };
};
```
(it's in the last 128k of Flash bank 0).

Trying to read from this on an `arduino_giga_r1//m7` or another H7 target should error at runtime.


**Expected behavior**

The partition should be accessed with no errors, as it was happening before commit 0e41b07309a893f1f5eafeede9bbeee237ccf8a4.
The problem with that change is that it replaces the _total size on chip_ with the _bank size_, which is half of the total on dual bank devices; this invalid value causes later safety checks to trip unnecessarily. 

PR incoming.

**Impact**
Depends on user partitioning; in Arduino it blocks the loader from working on H7 targets (Giga, Portenta H7, Opta).

**Additional context**

Tested with recent `main` (649eb6280da).

zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#94027.body:
### Describe the bug

I am having trouble with the nxp,pcf857x gpio driver. When I set pins as outputs everything works exactly as expected. 
The pcf857x chip only has one bit of storage for each pin. if the bit is set high then the pin is weakly pulled up (about 100uA), and if the bit is set low the output sinks current (about 25mA), an engineer would consider this an open drain output. 
An I2C write operation sends 8 (or 16) bits of data, the data sets the 8 (or 16) outputs to high or low. 
An I2C read operation reads the state of the 8 (or 16) voltages at the pins (independent of how the outputs are programmed).
In order to use a pin an an input, the Output register MUST be set to HIGH, otherwise the open drain is active and the signal is driven low. 
When i configure a pin as an input the driver always sets the corresponding output data to LOW, which pulls the pin low and it can't be used as an input. 
The driver should set the data for the pins that are configured as inputs to HIGH, unfortunately it does the opposite and makes the pins useless. 

### Regression

- [ ] This is a regression.

### Steps to reproduce

- connect a pcf9575 board to power and I2C. I am using an adafruit_feather_nrf52840, but any processor with I2C should work.
- define the i2c connections of the nxp,pcf857x in the devicetree (see app.overlay below).
- build and run test program (see main.c below). 
- correct output is pin state=1, if pin_state=0 then the issue exists.
- With a voltmeter measure the voltage at the io pin, it should be above 3V, if it is ~0V then the pin is being driven low.


Here is my 'hack' that makes it work, but I don't think this is the right way to do this:
```
diff --git a/drivers/gpio/gpio_pcf857x.c b/drivers/gpio/gpio_pcf857x.c
index b14e54cbd9a..c5a1baf9799 100644
--- a/drivers/gpio/gpio_pcf857x.c
+++ b/drivers/gpio/gpio_pcf857x.c
@@ -185,7 +185,7 @@ static int pcf857x_port_set_raw(const struct device *dev, uint16_t mask, uint16_
        tx_buf = (drv_data->pins_cfg.outputs_state & ~mask);
        tx_buf |= (value & mask);
        tx_buf ^= toggle;
-       sys_put_le16(tx_buf, tx_buf_p);
+       sys_put_le16(tx_buf|(~drv_data->pins_cfg.configured_as_outputs), tx_buf_p);     /* LJK all inputs must be driven high */

        rc = i2c_write_dt(&drv_cfg->i2c, tx_buf_p, drv_data->num_bytes);
        if (rc != 0) {
```
app.overlay
```
&i2c0 {
	gpio_bank: pcf8575@20 {
		compatible = "nxp,pcf857x";
		reg = <0x20>;
		gpio-controller;
		ngpios = <16>;
		#gpio-cells = <2>;
	};
};

/{
	inputs {
		compatible = "gpio-keys";
		input_d0: d0 {
				gpios = <&gpio_bank 0 GPIO_ACTIVE_HIGH>;
				label = "Input 1";
		};
	};

	aliases {
		input1 = &input_d0;
	};
};
```
main.c
```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <zephyr/kernel.h>
#include <zephyr/drivers/gpio.h>

struct gpio_dt_spec input = GPIO_DT_SPEC_GET(DT_ALIAS(input1), gpios);

int main(void)
{
int state, ret;

	printf("Test pcf857x input\n");
	ret = gpio_is_ready_dt(&input);
	if (ret<0) {
		printf("Error: input device %s is not ready\n", input.port->name);
		return ret;
	}
	ret = gpio_pin_configure_dt(&input, GPIO_INPUT);
	if (ret<0) {
		printf("Error: can not configure device %s as GPIO_INPUT\n", input.port->name);
		return ret;
	}
	state = gpio_pin_get(input.port, input.pin);
	printf("pin state = %d, should be \"1\"\n", state);
	return 0;
}
```


### Relevant log output

```shell
*** Booting Zephyr OS build v4.1.0 ***
Test pcf857x input
pin state = 1, should be "1"
```

### Impact

Functional Limitation – Some features not working as expected, but system usable.

### Environment

- OS: Linux 22.04
- Toolchain: zephyr-sdk-0.17.0
- Commit: Zephyr v4.1.0

### Additional Context

