zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#99164.body:
### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.

I wanted to implement Ethernet support for the STM32H7S78-DK board, which under Zephyr at the moment doesn't officially support Ethernet.

I based my work on the STM32H7S3L8 board (with adapted pins) and successfully tested Ethernet using the [dumb_http_server](https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/issues/2927) sample.

Before opening a PR, I’d like feedback on one implementation detail.

The setup for Ethernet DMA in `mpu_regions.c` depends on `sram2`:
https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/blob/91b1b84eee8159ce9706e8e0a3826cea04a09170/soc/st/stm32/stm32h7rsx/mpu_regions.c#L33-L42
But `sram2` is currently disabled, so the MPU regions are not created unless the user manually enables it:
https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/blob/91b1b84eee8159ce9706e8e0a3826cea04a09170/dts/arm/st/h7rs/stm32h7rs.dtsi#L67-L77

### Describe the solution you'd like

There are two different ways of solving this, at least known to me at this moment:

1. Enabling `sram2` in [stm32h7s78_dk-common.dtsi](https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/blob/main/boards/st/stm32h7s78_dk/stm32h7s78_dk-common.dtsi) and reducing the `sram0` by 16KB:
```
&sram0 {
	reg = <0x24000000 DT_SIZE_K(440)>;
};

...

&sram2 {
	status = "okay";
	zephyr,memory-attr = <DT_MEM_ARM(ATTR_MPU_RAM)>;
};
```

2. Replacing `sram2` with `sram1` here (or creating a fallback, if `sram2` is not available):
https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/blob/91b1b84eee8159ce9706e8e0a3826cea04a09170/soc/st/stm32/stm32h7rsx/mpu_regions.c#L33-L42

I think this ties, at least partially, to this issue: #98866, since I needed to enable `CONFIG_SPEED_OPTIMIZATIONS=y` in order to avoid MPU FAULT.

If this is a good way to implement Ethernet support for this board, I will gladly open a PR with these and other needed changes to enable Ethernet.

Thanks in advance.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

_No response_

zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#99479.body:
### Describe the bug

NXP RT1061 LPI2C can’t perform read requests larger than 1024 bytes. When I tried to read 4096 bytes from an I2C slave (EEPROM) on LPI2C2
```
&lpi2c2 {
    status = "okay";
	pinctrl-0 = <&pinmux_lpi2c2>;
	pinctrl-names = "default";
	eeprom0: eeprom@50 {
		/* M24512-RMN6TP (512 kbit eeprom in) */
		compatible = "st,m24512", "st,m24xxx", "atmel,at24";
		reg = <0x50>;
		size = <DT_SIZE_K(64)>;
		pagesize = <128>;
		address-width = <16>;
		timeout = <5>;
	};
```
in a single call, `eeprom_read()` returned `-EIO`. Using a debugger, I found that the failure occurs in [(fsl_lpi2c.c line 1612)](https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/hal_nxp/blob/master/mcux/mcux-sdk-ng/drivers/lpi2c/fsl_lpi2c.c#L1612), where the HAL limits I2C read transactions to 1024 bytes. This limitation is not mentioned in Zephyr’s I2C API, and application code should not need to handle target-specific restrictions. The driver or HAL layer should encapsulate this limitation by automatically chunking the transfer rather than forcing user code to be aware of hardware-dependent limits. Every transaction of 1024 bytes or less works as expected. By the way, it seems that this file does not account for `kStatus_InvalidArgument` in the documentation when listing the possible return codes.

