### Describe the bug

Hello, 
I am doing some GUI using Display Zephyr API on NXP boards.
I am facing an issue, when I want to write a buffer that is the size of the display, I have an offset of 3 pixels from the left column.
I only reproduced the issue with  ` drivers/display/display_mcux_elcdif.c` driver.

Tested and reproduced on both setup: 

- i.MXRT1170-EVK with rk055hdmipi4ma0 display
- i.MXRT1060-EVK with rk043fn66hs_ctg display

The issue seems to be inside `drivers/display/display_mcux_elcdif.c` when I go on this part of the `mcux_elcdif_write` method: https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/blob/main/drivers/display/display_mcux_elcdif.c#L92-L97
It has been introduced during this commit: https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/commit/4ae5edcf84b4eba24c96fbacc2b6d2dec6bc1359

If I reduce the height of the buffer (e.g. `display_heigt - 1`), then I no longer have the issue but it includes an additional copy inside the driver.

### Regression

- [x] This is a regression.

### Steps to reproduce

1. Use [drivers_display](https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr/tree/main/samples/drivers/display) sample.
2. Update `main` method with the following code that draw a buffer that is the size of the screen. 1st column is yellow and the last column is blue. 
```

int main(void)
{
    uint8_t *buf;
    const struct device *display_dev;
    struct display_capabilities capabilities;
    struct display_buffer_descriptor buf_desc;
    size_t buf_size = 0;

    display_dev = DEVICE_DT_GET(DT_CHOSEN(zephyr_display));
    if (!device_is_ready(display_dev)) {
        LOG_ERR("Device %s not found. Aborting sample.",
            display_dev->name);
#ifdef CONFIG_ARCH_POSIX
        posix_exit_main(1);
#else
        return 0;
#endif
    }

    display_get_capabilities(display_dev, &capabilities);

    buf_size = capabilities.x_resolution * capabilities.y_resolution * capabilities.current_pixel_format / 8;

    buf = k_malloc(buf_size);

    if (buf == NULL) {
        LOG_ERR("Could not allocate memory. Aborting sample.");
#ifdef CONFIG_ARCH_POSIX
        posix_exit_main(1);
#else
        return 0;
#endif
    }

    buf_desc.buf_size = buf_size;
    buf_desc.width = capabilities.x_resolution;
    buf_desc.height = capabilities.y_resolution;
    buf_desc.pitch = capabilities.x_resolution;

    (void)memset(buf, 0xFF, buf_size);

    // First column yellow 
    for (int y = 0; y < buf_desc.height; y++) { 
        buf[y * buf_desc.pitch * 2] = 0x00; 
        buf[y * buf_desc.pitch * 2 + 1] = 0xFF; 
    }

    // Last column blue 
    for (int y = 0; y < buf_desc.height; y++) { 
        buf[(y + 1) * buf_desc.pitch * 2 - 2] = 0xF0; 
        buf[(y + 1) * buf_desc.pitch * 2 - 1] = 0x00; 
    }

    display_write(display_dev, 0, 0, &buf_desc, buf);

#ifdef CONFIG_ARCH_POSIX
    posix_exit_main(0);
#endif
    return 0;
}
```
3. Flash a board using `display_mcux_elcdif` driver. The yellow column should appear at the 3rd column and the blue at the 2nd one.
4. Reduce the height of the buffer inside main method : `buf_desc.height = capabilities.y_resolution - 1` 
5. Flash a board, the yellow/blue columns should be displayed at the first/last columns as wanted.

