zephyrproject-rtos/zephyr#104604.body:
### Summary

The Zephyr networking stack allows for interfaces to join and leave multicast groups using IGMP (IPv4) or MLD (IPv6).

However the current implementation has a flaw, that if different subsystems join the same multicast address and one of those leaves, the multicast group will be left for all.

Demo snippet:

```c
#include <zephyr/net/igmp.h>
#include <zephyr/net/net_if.h>

struct net_if *iface = net_if_get_default();
struct net_in_addr group = { .s4_addr = { 224, 0, 0, 1 } };

/* First join: succeeds */
int ret = net_ipv4_igmp_join(iface, &group, NULL);
zassert_equal(ret, 0);

/* Second join of the same group: -EALREADY */
ret = net_ipv4_igmp_join(iface, &group, NULL);
zassert_equal(ret, -EALREADY);

/* First leave: succeeds */
ret = net_ipv4_igmp_leave(iface, &group);
zassert_equal(ret, 0);

/* Second leave: -ENOENT */
ret = net_ipv4_igmp_leave(iface, &group);
zassert_equal(ret, -ENOENT);
```

Now imagine the joins are done by unrelated subsystems, they are required to subscribe to network events to re-join a multicast group.

### Describe the solution you'd like

An enhancement would be to count the number of times a certain multicast address is joined/left, emitting the join on first creation and emitting the leave if the counter reaches zero again.

### Alternatives

Leave as is.

### Additional Context

For IGMPv3 additional include/exclude addresses can be provided, which complicates group membership comparison.

